Q: What are mutt modes?
There are two modes in which mail is read in Mutt. 
The first is the index of messages in the mailbox, which is called the ``index'' in Mutt. 
The second mode is the display of the message contents. This is called the ``pager.''

Q: How to send mails with mutt?

mutt -s "Party Invitation" faber bolte george -c lharden jrickard -b lin -a attachment.png < invitation

This sends the contents of the file "invitation" from your current working directory 
with the subject header (-s) "Party Invitation" to faber, bolte, and george, 
with carbon copies (-c) to lharden and jrickard and a blind carbon copy (-b) to lin.
There is one attached file.

#---------------------------------------------------------------------- 
# MIME

Q: What are MIME documents?
There is one standard technique for sending multimedia through email, it's called MIME.
Mutt supports both sending and receiving it. 
MIME is an acronym for Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions

Q: Mailcap file?
Mutt, like many other mime aware tools, refers to the mailcap configuration file 
for instructions on viewing different types of mime-encoded mail attachments.
There are two likely locations for your mailcap file; 
* /etc/mailcap for system-wide settings 
* ~/.mailcap where you should add entries you create or modify as a normal user
